":false,"ts_bgc":"#93e3ed","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":8613,"ei":8630,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}}]; DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart = new Date().getTime(); _getTimingInstance().incrementTime(, DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart - DOCS_modelChunkParseStart); DOCS_warmStartDocumentLoader.loadModelChunk(DOCS_modelChunk); DOCS_modelChunk = undefined;</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="KMmp6aBwsrBP5pb5N6gEt8XdwBw"  nonce="KMmp6aBwsrBP5pb5N6gEt8XdwBw">DOCS_modelChunkParseStart = new Date().getTime();</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="KMmp6aBwsrBP5pb5N6gEt8XdwBw"  nonce="KMmp6aBwsrBP5pb5N6gEt8XdwBw">DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":8637,"s":"\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cMost of the time, you should be using the positive/playful voice. It’s the voice of an easygoing, good-natured person. Your attitude is light and encouraging. The key here is to relax and smile while you’re talking.\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c35\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001ctalking on the phone, has an impact tonally that the other person will pick up on\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c35\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cMirroring, also called isopraxism, is essentially imitation. It’s another neurobehavior humans (and other animals) display in which we copy each other to comfort each other. It can be done with speech patterns, body language, vocabulary, tempo, and tone of voice. It’s generally an unconscious behavior—we are rarely aware of it when it’s happening—but it’s a sign that people are bonding, in sync, and establishing the kind of rapport that leads to trust. It’s a phenomenon (and now technique) that follows a very basic but\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c37\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cprofound biological principle: We fear what’s different and are drawn to what’s similar. As the saying goes, birds of a feather flock together. Mirroring, then, when practiced consciously, is the art of insinuating similarity. “Trust me,” a mirror signals to another’s unconscious, “You and I—we’re alike.”\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c38\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cIt’s almost laughably simple: for the FBI, a “mirror” is when you repeat the\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c38\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001clast three words (or the critical one to three words) of what someone has just said. Of the entirety of the FBI’s hostage negotiation skill set, mirroring is the closest one gets to a Jedi mind trick. Simple, and yet uncannily effective. By repeating back what people say, you trigger this mirroring instinct and your counterpart will inevitably elaborate on what was just said and sustain the process of connecting\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c38\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cUse the late-night FM DJ voice. 2.Start with “I’m sorry . . .” 3.Mirror. 4.Silence. At least four seconds, to let the mirror work its magic on your counterpart. 5.Repeat.\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c46\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cPopping his head into her office, the boss said, “Let’s make two copies of all the paperwork.” “I’m sorry, two copies?” she mirrored in response, remembering not only the DJ voice, but to deliver the mirror in an inquisitive tone. The intention behind most mirrors should be “Please, help me understand.” Every\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c46\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001ctime you mirror someone, they will reword what they’ve said. They will never say it exactly the same way they said it the first time. Ask someone, “What do you mean by that?” and you’re likely to incite irritation or defensiveness. A mirror, however, will get you the clarity you want while signaling respect and concern for what the other person is saying. “Yes,” her boss responded, “one for us and one for the customer.” “I’m sorry, so you are saying that the client is asking for a copy and we need a copy for internal use?” “Actually, I’ll check with the client—they haven’t asked for anything. But I definitely want a copy. That’s just how I do business.” “Absolutely,” she responded. “Thanks for checking with the customer. Where would you like to store the in-house copy? There’s no more space in the file room here.”\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c46\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cMirroring will make you feel awkward as heck when you first try it. That’s the only hard part about it; the\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c47\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001ctechnique takes a little practice. Once you get the hang of it, though, it’ll become a conversational Swiss Army knife valuable in just about every professional and social setting.\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c47\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c48\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nHow to Create Trust with Tactical Empathy\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001ca soothing voice, close listening, and a calm repetition of the words of your “patient” can get you a lot further than a cold, rational argument. It may sound touchy-feely, but if you can perceive the emotions of others, you have a chance to turn them to your advantage. The more you know about someone, the more power you have.\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c51\n\u0011\n\u0011"},{"ty":"te","id":"i.21","spi":8646},{"ty":"te","id":"i.22","spi":8899},{"ty":"te","id":"i.23","spi":9018},{"ty":"te","id":"i.24","spi":9580},{"ty":"te","id":"i.25","spi":9924},{"ty":"te","id":"i.26","spi":10038},{"ty":"te","id":"i.27","spi":10491},{"ty":"te","id":"i.28","spi":10699},{"ty":"te","id":"i.29","spi":11047},{"ty":"te","id":"i.30","spi":11910},{"ty":"