se,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_fs":13.0,"ts_ff":"Droid Serif","ts_it_i":false,"ts_bgc":"#ffb8a1","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":16600,"ei":16617,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":16636,"ei":17267,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_fs":13.0,"ts_ff":"Droid Serif","ts_it_i":false,"ts_bgc":"#fde096","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":17268,"ei":17285,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}}]; DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart = new Date().getTime(); _getTimingInstance().incrementTime(, DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart - DOCS_modelChunkParseStart); DOCS_warmStartDocumentLoader.loadModelChunk(DOCS_modelChunk); DOCS_modelChunk = undefined;</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="KMmp6aBwsrBP5pb5N6gEt8XdwBw"  nonce="KMmp6aBwsrBP5pb5N6gEt8XdwBw">DOCS_modelChunkParseStart = new Date().getTime();</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="KMmp6aBwsrBP5pb5N6gEt8XdwBw"  nonce="KMmp6aBwsrBP5pb5N6gEt8XdwBw">DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":17292,"s":"\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c63\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cIn case you’re worried about volunteering to role-play with me in front of the class, I want to tell you in advance . . . it’s going to be horrible.” After the laughter dies down, I then say, “And those of you who do volunteer will probably get more out of this than anyone else.” I always end up with more volunteers than I need. Now, look at what I did: I prefaced the conversation by labeling my audience’s fears; how much worse can something be than “horrible”? I defuse them and wait, letting it sink in and thereby making the unreasonable seem less forbidding.\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c63\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c71\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cThese tools, then, are nothing less than emotional best practices that help you cure the pervasive ineptitude that marks our most critical conversations in life. They will help you connect and create more meaningful and warm relationships. That they might help you extract what you want is a bonus; human connection is the first goal. With that in mind, I encourage you to take the risk of sprinkling these in every conversation you have. I promise you that they will feel awkward and artificial at first, but keep at it. Learning to walk felt awfully strange, too.\n\nCan we integrate AI with negotiation and suggest moocs, partners?\n\nOctober 16, 2016\n\u001c71\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nHow to Generate Momentum and Make It Safe to Reveal the Real Stakes\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001c“NO” STARTS THE NEGOTIATION\n\nOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c74\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cThe emotional terrain was complex, changing, and often conflicting. To successfully gain a hostage’s safe release, a negotiator had to penetrate the hostage-taker’s motives, state of mind, intelligence, and emotional strengths and weaknesses. The negotiator played the role of bully, conciliator, enforcer, savior, confessor, instigator, and peacemaker—and that’s just a few of the parts.\n\nOctober 22, 2016\n\u001c74\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c75\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001ca lieutenant’s job is to say, ‘No.’” At first, I thought that sort of automated response signaled a failure of imagination. But then I realized I did the same thing with my teenage son, and that after I’d said “No” to him, I often found that I was open to hearing what he had to say. That’s because having protected myself, I could relax and more easily consider the possibilities. “No” is the start of the negotiation, not the end of it. We’ve been conditioned to fear the word “No.” But it is a statement of perception far more often than of fact. It seldom means, “I have considered all the facts and made a rational choice.” Instead, “No” is often a decision, frequently temporary, to maintain the status quo. Change is scary, and “No” provides a little protection from that scariness.\n\nOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c76\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cgive their adversary (his word for counterpart) permission to say “No” from the outset of a negotiation. He calls it “the right to veto.” He observes that people will fight to the death to preserve their right to say “No,” so give them that right and the negotiating environment becomes more constructive and collaborative almost immediately.\n\nOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c76\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cdeep and universal human need for autonomy. People need to feel in control.\n\nOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c77\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cPolitely saying “No” to your opponent (we’ll go into this in more depth in Chapter 9), calmly hearing “No,” and just letting the other side know that they are welcome to say “No” has a positive impact on any negotiation. In fact, your invitation for the other side to say “No” has an amazing power to bring down barriers and allow for beneficial communication\n\nOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c77\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c77\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c77\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c78\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cHuman beings the world over are so used to being pursued for the commitment “yes” as a condition to find out more that they have become masters at giving the counterfeit “yes.”\n\nOctober 23, 2016\n\u001c79\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cgood negotiators know that their job isn’t to put on a great performance but to gently guide their counterpart to discover their goal as his own.\n\nOctober 24, 2016\n\u001c79\n\u0011\n\u0011"},{"ty":"te","id":"i.43","spi":17301},{"ty":"te","id":"i.44","spi":17337},{"ty":"te","id":"i.45","spi":17941},{"ty":"te","id":"i.46","spi":17977},{"ty":"te","id":"i.47","spi":18717},{"ty":"te","id":"i.48","spi":18782},{"ty":"te","id":"i.49","spi":19208},{"ty":"te","id":"i.50","spi":19244},{"ty":"te","id":"i.51","spi":20071},{"ty":"te","id":"i.52","spi":20451},{"ty":"te","id":"i.53","spi":20564},{"ty":"te","id":"i.54","spi":20961},{"ty":"te","id":"i.55","spi":20997},{"ty":"te","id":"i.56","spi":21033},{"ty":"te","id":"i.57","spi":21069},{"ty":"te","id":"i.58","spi":21283},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":17292,"ei":17292,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_sb_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_ls":1.0,"ps_sa_i":true,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_kwn_i":true,"ps_ifl_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_il_i":true,"ps_ir_i":true,"ps_al_i":true}},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":17293,"ei":17293,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_sb_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_ls":1.0,"ps_sa_i":true,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_kwn_i":true,"ps_ifl_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_il_i":true,"ps_ir_i":true,"ps_al_i":true}},{"ty":"as","st":"tbl","si":17294,"ei":17294,"sm":{"tbls_cols":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[{"col_wv":468.0,"col_wt":0}]}},"tbls_bw":0.75,"tbls_bc":"#bdbdbd"}},{"ty":"as","st":"cell","si":17296,"ei":17296,"sm":{"cell_pb_i":false,"cell_pr_i":false,"cell_pt_i":false,"cell_pt":0.0,"cell_pb":0.0,"cell_pr":0.0,"cell_pl_i":false,"cell_pl":0.0}},{"ty":"as","st":"tbl","si":17298,"ei":17298,"sm":{"tbls_cols":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[{"col_wv":54.0,"col_wt":0},{"col_wv":358.5,"col_wt":0},{"col_wv":54.0,"co